Recall: 0.15789: Kishinev pogrom: A three-day pogrom began, which would leave forty-seven Jews dead.
Russo-Japanese War: Japan launched a surprise torpedo attack on the Russian navy at Port Arthur.

Bloody Sunday (1905): Peaceful demonstrators arrived at the Winter Palace in Saint Petersburg to present a petition to the tsar, leading was a priest named Georgi Gapon. The Imperial Guard fired on the crowd, killing around 200 and wounding 800.
Russian legislative election, 1906: The first free elections to the Duma gave majorities to liberal and socialist parties.
Nicholas changed the electoral law and gave greater electoral value to the votes of nobility and landowners.

Recall: 0.15789: Lena goldfields massacre: The Russian army fired on a crowd of striking miners, killing 150.
Assassination of Archduke Franz Ferdinand: Archduke Franz Ferdinand of Austria was assassinated by Gavrilo Princip of the Bosnian separatist group Young Bosnia.
Gorlice-TarnÃ³w Offensive: The German army launched an offensive across the length of the Eastern Front.
Basmachi Revolt: Nicholas issued a decree ordering the conscription of Central Asians.
February Revolution: The workers at the Putilov Plant in Petrograd went on strike.
July Days: A spontaneous pro-soviet demonstration occurred on the streets of Petrograd.
Alexander Kerensky succeeded L'vov as Prime Minister.
Kornilov Affair: General Lavr Kornilov ordered an army corps to Petrograd to destroy the soviets.
Estonian Bolsheviks under Jaan Anvelt captured the capital, Tallinn.
